                <h2><strong>What is community based surveillance?</strong></h2>
                <div style="text-align:justify;">
                   
                        Community-based surveillance (CBS) is an important strategy to broaden the reach of public health surveillance to rural communities in resource poor settings,
                        especially those facing or at risk of disease outbreaks. </br> CBS is the organised and rapid capture of information by and for community members about events that occur in their own communities.
                        Real-time reporting to the Red Cross and health authorities enables early detection of and response to events that pose a threat to public health.</br>
                        The continuous monitoring and information sharing enables a tailoring of community-based health programme to respond to current threats and community needs as they change over time.</br>
                        CBS is designed for scale and sustainability by employing cheap and accessible mobile technology and utilising existing Red Cross volunteer networks in response to disease outbreaks.
                   
                </div>
                </div>
            <div class="col-lg-5 features-text">
                <h2><strong>CBS in Madagascar</strong></h2>
                <div style="text-align:justify;">
                        Malagasy Red Cross is implementing CBS as a pilot addition to existing community based health programmes in 2016.
                        CBS is targeting the detection and reporting of events that indicate a risk of plague and the spread of diarrhoeal disease.</br></br>
                                       
                        Red Cross volunteers are trained to detect, respond to  and report these events using simple community case- and event definitions.
                        Reports are sent to a central database by SMS and automatically processed in real time.
                        The data dashboards are updated eight times per day on the CBS website, and MRC staff and relevant authorities will have access to the real- time data.
                        If number of reports reach a set threshold, MRC regional coordinator will follow up with the relevant local authorities who supports the community in the response and/or undertakes an investigation.
                        The MRC will respond with community activities, particularly sensitisation on necessary health topics identified as necessary through the CBS reporting.
                        
                    
                </div>
