            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-0 features-text">
                    <small>CBS</small>
                    <h2>Real time SMS reporting </h2>

                    <i class="fa fa-bar-chart big-icon pull-right"></i>
                                      
                            <div style="text-align:justify;">
                                <p>
                                    Using simple SMS for data collection and reporting keeps cost minimal and allows CBS to be implemented in hard-to-reach areas with limited infrastructure.
                                    The SMS reports are coded using numbers, which allows all community members to participate, and reduces the risk of error in reporting.
                                    In areas with low mobile penetration and network service, SMS is more reliable than mobile data transfer. With limited electricity and charging possibilities,
                                    a ‘dumb phone’ battery lasts longer than a smartphone, and if volunteers do not already own a phone, the cost of feature phones and the cost of SMS does not impact the scalability of CBS.
                                    SMS is therefore suitable for simple reporting such as for CBS and early warning.
                                </p>
                            </div>

                    </div>
                <div class="col-lg-6 features-text">
                    <small>CBS</small>
                    <h2>Alerts</h2>
                    <i class="fa fa-bolt big-icon pull-right"></i>
                    <div style="text-align:justify;">
                        <p>
                            The Red Cross Red Crescent Movement only partakes in surveillance initiatives when it is required in order to detect events of public health importance and respond to avert an outbreak or a crisis.
                            Therefor the most important CBS principles is the alerting of relevant authorities for timely and adequate response. In Madagascar, the SMS reports submitted by the volunteers,
                            can be continuously followed by the relevant authorities/people who has been granted access to the specific disease data. When reports reach a set threshold, the MRC regional coordinator will follow up with the right authorities,
                            who are responsible for follow up of the alert through, case investigation. MRC will be supporting community response such as e.g. clean up campaigns.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-0 features-text">
                    <small>CBS</small>
                    <h2>Real time analysis  and data sharing</h2>
                    <i class="fa fa-bar-chart big-icon pull-right"></i>
                    <div style="text-align:justify;">
                        <p>
                            SMS data is fed to a central database which is connected to the analysis and visualisation tool Microsoft Power BI and a CBS designated website.
                            Data is refreshed eight times per day and gives the user virtually real-time information access through the website and/or through Power BI dashboards.  </br>
                            Data is shared with defined users only, who require access to the information in order to support the project and communities that take part.
                            This includes the Malagasy Red Cross health and technical staff, Malagasy Ministry of health division for sanitation and epidemiological surveillance, local authorities and health clinic staff.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                <div class="col-lg-6 features-text">
                    <small>CBS</small>
                    <h2>Confidentiality and privacy policy</h2>
                    <i class="fa fa-users big-icon pull-right"></i>
                    <div style="text-align:justify;">
                        <p>
                            Red Cross staff and volunteers engaged in CBS are bound by the principle of confidentiality.
                            Confidentiality is of fundamental importance for the Red Cross and it emanates from the Seven Fundamental Principles with emphasis on the principles of Neutrality and Independence.
                            Confidentiality in this context means that Red Cross staff and volunteers can only share personal information if there is a consent from the person concerned or if other statutory conditions are met.
                            Although no identifiable information such as name, identification number or address is collected by the volunteers, health information is defined as personal information and is therefore treated as sensitive.
                            As response is integral to community based surveillance, a person’s identity could potentially be identified to health authorities and the community if response is required.
                            Therefore, Malagasy Red Cross is taking every possible step to protect privacy and adhere to confidentiality principles by: </br>
                            Obtaining informed consent: from community leaders and the community members before implementation of CBS.</br>
                            Acting sensitively: in the case of e.g. a suspect plague case in the community the volunteers will work only with the concerned household and health authorities in order to avoid revealing the sensitive information about a person’s health to the community or others;  </br>
                            Protecting the data: during data transmission using widely used standard secure data protection protocol SSL/TLS/VPN. Any data that should be viewed by a restricted audience follows industry best practices for authentication, using single-sign-on systems like Microsoft Active Directory and two factor authentication to perform user authentication.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    </div>
            </div>
        </div>

